 Le Willows, Suffolk, England":"Walsham le Willows, Suffolk, England","Nayland, Suffolk, England":"Nayland, Suffolk, England","Chesham, Chiltern District, Buckinghamshire, England":"Chesham, Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","Nayland, Suffolk, , England":"Nayland, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","Nayland, Babergh District, Suffolk, England":"Nayland, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Cornwallis","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman, English: regional name for someone from Cornwall, a Normanized form of Middle English  <i>Cornwalish</i>.  Compare  Cornwall  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Cornwall","meanings":["English:","habitational name from the county of Cornwall, which is named with the Old English tribal name <i>Cornwealas</i>. This is from <i>Kernow</i> (the term that the Cornish used to refer to themselves, a word of uncertain etymology, perhaps connected with a Celtic element meaning ‘horn, headland’), + Old English <i>wealas</i> ‘strangers, foreigners’, the term used by the Anglo-Saxons for British-speaking people.","variant of   Cornwell  ."]},{"name":"Cornish","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): habitational name for someone from the county of Cornwall, from Middle English <i>Cornish</i>, <i>Cornysh</i> formed on the analogy of <i>English</i>, which was usually Normanized as <i>Corneys</i>. Not surprisingly, the surname is common in adjacent Devon, but it is also established as far afield as Suffolk and London."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret Cornwallis was born after 1506, in Nayland, Suffolk, England, Unit